"# Chapter 7 — Amiga — multitasking, custom chips

The Commodore Amiga. First machine, the Amiga 1000, released July
1985. Designed by a team at Amiga Corporation (originally Hi-Toro)
led by Jay Miner — the same designer who did the Atari 800's custom
chips. Amiga Corporation was acquired by Commodore in 1984, and the
1000 shipped under the Commodore name.

The Amiga was, in 1985, generations ahead of anything else at its
price point. It had 4096 colors on screen when the Mac had 1 (black
or white). It had preemptive multitasking when the Mac was
cooperative-only. It had four channels of stereo sampled audio when
the PC was still doing PC-speaker beeps. And it cost less than the
Mac.

## The processor

Motorola 68000. Sixteen 32-bit registers (though the ALU is
technically 16-bit internally). Clock speed on the Amiga 1000: 7.14
MHz on PAL. A big step up from the 8-bit 6502-family machines.

The 68000 was a well-designed processor. Its instruction set is
relatively regular. It has good support for high-level languages
(displacements, complex addressing modes, memory-to-memory
operations). It became the standard for late-1980s workstations and
home computers — the Mac used it, Atari ST used it, Sega Genesis
used it, arcade machines from Neo Geo to Capcom's CPS-1 used it.

But the Amiga's story isn't really about the 68000. It's about the
custom chips.

## The chipset

Three custom chips, code-named after women in Jay Miner's life and
his colleagues':

- **Agnus**: address generator, blitter, and copper. Agnus arbitrates
  memory access between the CPU and the other chips. Agnus contains
  the blitter (a block-image transfer engine — hardware that copies
  and combines rectangles of graphics memory at extremely high speed)
  and the copper (a display-list-driven coprocessor that can change
  hardware register values on specific scan lines).

- **Denise**: video output. Handles the display generator, sprites,
  playfield, and color palette. Denise is what actually creates the
  video signal that goes to your monitor.

- **Paula**: audio, floppy, and serial I/O. Four audio channels
  (two per stereo side), each an 8-bit sampled sound stream at
  arbitrary rate. The floppy controller. The keyboard scanner.
  Various I/O.

Together the chipset is called OCS (Original Chip Set). Later
machines had ECS (Enhanced Chip Set) and AGA (Advanced Graphics
Architecture). But OCS is the classic.

## The Copper

The Amiga's Copper is worth its own paragraph. It's a display-list
coprocessor like the Atari ANTIC, but more powerful. The Copper's
program runs in sync with the video beam. It can wait for a specific
scan line, then write to a hardware register (change colors, move
sprites, switch display modes, whatever), then wait for another
scan line, and so on.

This is how the Amiga does its trademark effects: the Copper changes
hardware colors on every scan line to produce a smooth gradient
across the screen; it changes sprite positions mid-frame to fake
'more sprites than the hardware actually has'; it swaps display
modes so the top of the screen can be text and the bottom can be
graphics.

The Copper is basically a small assembly language for the video
system. Programmers wrote 'copper lists' — sequences of MOVE and WAIT
instructions — that specified exactly what should happen at what
scan line. The results looked like nothing else in 1985.

## The blitter

Agnus's blitter is a hardware block-image copy engine. Give it a
source rectangle in memory, a destination rectangle, an optional
mask, and a Boolean operation to combine them (AND, OR, XOR, invert,
and various combinations). The blitter runs at full memory speed,
much faster than the 68000 could copy the same data.

Every scrolling game, every windowed graphical operation, every
character drawing on the Amiga used the blitter. It's what made
graphical multitasking possible on 1985 hardware — the CPU could
run programs while the blitter handled the graphics work.

## Preemptive multitasking

AmigaOS 1.0 shipped with preemptive multitasking. That means the
operating system's scheduler could interrupt any running program to
give another one a turn — the programs didn't have to voluntarily
yield.

Preemptive multitasking was standard on mainframes and minicomputers
by 1985, but on consumer-priced hardware it was rare. The Mac used
cooperative multitasking (Multi-Finder, 1988) until OS X (2001). MS
Windows didn't get proper preemptive multitasking until Windows NT
in 1993 and consumer Windows in Windows 95 / NT-line derivatives.

So: the Amiga in 1985 had a multitasking OS that PCs wouldn't have
in a mainstream form for another decade. This is why Amiga users are
still nostalgic. The machine's OS felt fundamentally more capable
than what would replace it.

## What Motoi owes the Amiga

The scheduler model. Motoi's runtime schedules carts and language-model
inference and cortex writes and UI updates all in parallel, borrowing
the spirit of preemptive multitasking — the runtime picks who runs
when, so no single cart can lock the whole system.

The custom-chip idea. Specialized hardware taking work off the main
CPU. In Motoi's software equivalent, the composer widgets run their
own animation loop independent of the language model.

The copper-list idea. Motoi's animation module lets you write
timelines — 'at frame 30, change color; at frame 60, move sprite' —
that a small scheduler executes. Same shape as the Copper, written
in Scheme.

## A tiny example

A copper-list-like timeline in Motoi Scheme:

```
(define timeline
  '((frame  0  (set-background 'black))
    (frame 30  (set-background 'blue))
    (frame 60  (spawn-sprite 'star :x 100 :y 50))
    (frame 90  (fade-to 'white 30))
    (frame 120 (end))))

(define (run-timeline tl)
  (let loop ((current-frame 0) (remaining tl))
    (cond
      ((null? remaining) 'done)
      (else
       (let* ((next (car remaining))
              (target-frame (cadr next))
              (action (caddr next)))
         (advance-to-frame target-frame)
         (eval-in-runtime action)
         (loop target-frame (cdr remaining)))))))

(run-timeline timeline)
```

That's how the Amiga Copper worked — as data, driven by a scheduler
running in parallel with the CPU.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

The Amiga is a machine designed by someone who understood the whole
stack — Jay Miner and his team. When you understand the whole stack
you can put specialized hardware exactly where it earns its keep,
and the resulting machine feels lighter than the sum of its parts.

Modern systems are almost always assembled from vendor pieces that
don't perfectly fit together. Something is lost. The Amiga is a
useful reminder of what's possible when a single team gets to design
the whole thing.

Alfred's list of old machines he loves includes the Amiga. There's a
reason.")
